segments.text: I'm sure that things made some impressions and influenced me but I don't remember any single events that stand out as really shaping myself or my future.
It was more of a lot of activities and events culminating in a pattern of activity and a pattern of efficiency, of commitment, of passion.
I found out

a lot of it trial and error just like you learn how to study that to be successful and to achieve things it takes because I didn't make I always knew that I wasn't intelligent but I always committed myself to getting

things done well by sweat staying after it recognizing that if it's important then be persistent and get it done and I always had a the thrill of knowing that the education I got here had equipped me to

serve in the entomology profession as an extension entomologist who worked with farmers and ranchers all over this state and homeowners on bug problems was important and that being able to solve those problems was what I wanted to be good at and never always was excited that I had the opportunity to do that and A&M gave me the

knowledge and the ability to think through some of those problems having grown up in a small ag community I understood the importance of people and being able to help them with a lot of times what you would view as small issues but are extremely important to be able to get
a solution to those that's practical and that they're capable of utilizing.
If you could have all the people that were part of your A&M experience here today which ones would you most want to thank and why?
Those that Dean Penberthy that advised you that cared
that were there when you had at that moment some significant trials and tribulations in your life.
Many of the entomology faculty that I learned about this industry and this profession from
I remember several of our Wesley Foundation directors that were important from the standpoint of developing the religious beliefs and the guideposts to living in right and wrong as being important.
was always a little bit of a rebel inside and at times it troubled me but it never changed much and so having people that support that chastise you when you get a little bit too far out of bounds

but that supports you on some of those activities and efforts that you put a lot into and hope will be valuable to society or a group within society, whether it be cotton producers or beekeepers or livestock producers with screw-arm eradication, but just the opportunity to have
met so many people that made a difference in others' lives.
Those are the things that impress you and that stay with you.
We're getting close to ending.
What have I left out that you might have thought of before we started that you'd want to be sure to get in here?
Have I left anything out?
I'm sure that we have, but I can't think of anything right off the top.
If we do, we can get them in the next edition.
What did it mean to you, what has it meant to your life that you attended Texas A&M?
Well, I'm certain that it,
meant the opportunity to be an entomologist and to do those things that I've done that would not have been afforded if I had gone anywhere else or done something else.
It's been such an integral part of my life since 55
that I think it would be impossible for me to say what it would be like if I had gone to Texas Tech or to West Texas.

The thing that I noticed when I was working up there at Tech in the summers and there were a lot of students around and the contacts I've had, there's a certain amount of discipline that you pick up at A&M that I'm afraid
And I'm sure it doesn't even exist today in the civilian population here.
But I'm reluctant to be critical of that segment of the population because the Corps only represents, what, less than 2,000 of the 43,000-something that we have here on campus.
But those were difficult days.
But they had a purpose.
What are the qualities of being an Aggie, the key ingredients?

I think it's a matter of self-confidence and of leadership qualities and of dedication and a commitment to a group of people that you learn to respect because they went through the same kinds of problems that you did.
OK, next to the last question.
Let's make believe that somebody walks up to you tomorrow morning, hands you a check for a million dollars with one condition.
You must pass it on to Texas A&M, but you decide what it is to be used for.
In other words, if you could make a big gift to A&M, what would you want A&M to do?
What would you want it?
I'd want it for scholarships.
For whom?
I would probably, for undergraduates, and I'd probably be a little bit picky about the Ag, College of Agriculture and designating.
How would you select the recipients?
Number one, I probably wouldn't select them.
I would ask the departments to do that.
But would it be on the basis of their height or their good looks?
I would want it to relate to the likelihood that they would be successful.
So it would be based on academic qualifications.
Probably interest in certain fields.
Such as?
Well, agriculture and entomology.
And I think those are to be expected of someone who went through in that program.
Last question.
What feelings do you carry in your heart for Texas A&M?
It's an everlasting love that is reserved for
your family, your God, and your school.
And they're very comparable.
